  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Reintroducing the laundered money into the economy as apparently legitimate funds.\n\nMoney laundering is considered a serious crime because it allows criminals to profit from illegal activities, undermines the integrity of financial institutions, and can have broader economic and social consequences. Laws and regulations aimed at preventing and punishing money laundering are in place in most jurisdictions, often requiring banks and other financial institutions to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities. Penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
